@node "bugs"

@{u}Bugs/Troubleshooting@{uu}

There should be no problems. But no program is perfect:
* A corrupt SProbe.conf can cause strange behaviour or the program may not
  run at all. So delete "SProbe.conf" if this happens, and rerun the program.

* Planets are not always displayed if dates prior to August 1999 are used.

If you find any bugs, then please email me at silverscope@redhotant.com.

@endnode

@node "hist"

@{u}History@{uu}

V1.0 -  Initial idea
	Started life as a small window, with odd looking sun and planets.
	Added a small window to allow dates to be entered.

V1.1 -	Made window sizeable. Added zoom function.

V1.2 -	Decided to use a custom screen and added planet icons instead of little
	dots! Fiddled about with the colours. Looking good!

V1.3 -	Made the planets positions more accurate. Added "NOW" button to the
	main control panel.

V1.31-	Added "height" and rotate adjustment control.

V1.4 -	Added menus.

V1.41-	Started on the Earth centred view mode. Found out that not displaying
	the orbits speeds up the re-display, so I made it optional.

V1.42-	Implemented save configuration function.
	Made the Earth centred view mode more useable with zoom and angle
	functions.

V1.43-	Now able to increase/decrease time in user definable steps.

V1.44-	Planets in heliocentric mode now respond to mouse clicks. Window opens
	detailing up to date information about planets.

V1.5 -  Now displays information about Meteor showers, opposition times for
        Mars, Jupiter and Saturn, morning/evening elongation times for Mercury
        and Venus.

V1.51-  Added Saturn ring aspect. Added Venus phase display.

@endnode

@node "instl"

@{u}Installation@{uu}

Just copy the "SolarProbe" directory and its contents over to your hard drive.

The full version should include the following in the "SolarProbe" directory:


SolarProbe                                The main program
SolarProbe.info
SProbe.doc                                Text document
SProbe.doc.info
SProbe.guide                              Manual
SProbe.guide.info
SolarProbe.readme              
SProbe.key                                Keyfile (Empty if unregistered)
SProbe.conf                               Prefs file
Data (dir)
  Planets.dat                             Planet symbols
  Planets1.dat                            Alternative planet symbols
  up.iff
  dn.iff                                  GUI elements

@endnode
@node "start"
@{u}First Steps@{uu}

After you start SolarProbe you will see a black screen with the sun at the
centre. Six planets should also be visible. In the top-right of the screen
is the control panel.

Experiment with the control panel for a while to get used to it!
The datestring allows you to enter in any date from 12/08/1999 in the format
"dd/mm/yyyy". If an invalid date string is entered then the date will reset
to 01/01/2000. At startup it should show the current date.

Pressing "NOW" Takes you to the current date.

The viewing position can be altered by using the control panel: +/- zooms in
and out, < & > rotates the solar system, UP and DOWN buttons alter the height
above the ecliptic plane.

clicking on "INCR" will advance the time by the number of days specified in
the "Time Increment" setting, located in the "Settings" menu.

Orbits can be toggled using the "Orbits" menu item in the "Settings" menu.

Planet names can be displayed under each planet by selecting the "Names"
option in the "Settings" menu.

Clicking on any planet will display information for that planet. All planets
have information suitable for beginners, but is also good for the more
experienced astronomer too. For example, clicking on Saturn brings up
opposition and ring-tilt information.

This mode is the external view of our solar system. Selecting the "Geocentric"
mode from the "Mode" menu, displays the solar system as seen from Earth.

At the moment, this viewmode only shows you the sun and five planets. As this
mode has no horizon, there is no need for your longitude, latitude etc.

Please note, if you are living south of the equator, this view would appear
to be upside-down. I will fix this very shortly.

The same control panel can be used to change the view:-
< & > buttons change the view position from sun to left and right.
+ & - zooms in and out.
At the widest viewing angle (360 degrees), the "opposition" line is visible,
this is the part of the sky opposite the sun and is therefore due south at
midnight. When planets move past this line they will appear on the other side
of the screen.


@endnode
