@node "qguide"

@{u}Observing the Planets@{uu}

Here is my quick guide to observing the planets.

@{u}The Sun@{uu}
  Sunspots can be observed with binoculars or telescope:
  On a clear day the sun's disc can be projected on to a piece of white card 
  placed about 20cm away from the eyepiece.
  Sunspots are darker areas of the sun and only last for a few days at a
  time. If you keep a record of the number of sunspots on the sun at any one
  time, you will notice that the number of spots varies over a period of 11
  years. During solar "maximum", the most sunspots can be seen. It is during
  this period that aurorae may be seen. The further north you are the easier
  it is to see these aurorae. I have seen one from south-west England in
  April 2000.

@{b}This guide will be completed for the next update (Free to registered users)@{ub}


@endnode
